3–Male":"1293–Deceased","1303–Male":"1303–Deceased","1240–Male":"1240–Deceased","1244–Female":"1244–Deceased","about 1293":"about 1293","1252":"1252","1263":"1263","1240":"1240","1261":"1261","1293":"1293","1290":"1290","Bef 1261":"before 1261","1303":"1303","1267":"1267","about 1303":"about 1303","1244":"1244","1265":"1265","Thurstanston, Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Thurstaston, Chester, England":"Thurstaston, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Claverly, Shropshire, England":"Claverley, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","Thurstanton, Chester, England, Great Britain":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Whitmore","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Whitmoor (Devon) or Whitmore (Staffordshire and Dorset), or from any of numerous other places in England with names denoting a white moor or mere (from Old English <i>hwīt</i> ‘white’ + <i>mōr</i> ‘moor’ or <i>mere</i> ‘pool’).","History: Francis Whitmore settled in Cambridge, MA, before 1648."],"variants":[{"name":"Whitemore","meanings":["English (Somerset): variant of   Whitmore  ."]},{"name":"Whittemore","meanings":["English (Bedfordshire): variant of   Whitmore  .","History: Thomas Whittemore came from England to Charlestown, MA, in or <i>c.</i> 1639. Amos Whittemore, born in Cambridge, MA, in 1759 was an inventor and gunsmith, and another Thomas Whittemore was born in Boston in 1800; he was a Universalist clergyman and MA legislator."]},{"name":"Whitmer","meanings":["English: variant of   Whitmore  .","Americanized form of German   Wittmeyer   or of   Wittmer  ."]},{"name":"Whitmarsh","meanings":["English: habitational name from Whitemarsh, a place in the parish of Sedgehill, Wiltshire, named from Old English <i>hwīt</i> ‘white’ (i.e. ‘phosphorescent’) + <i>mersc</i> ‘marsh’. Compare   Whitmore  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William De  Whitmore was born before 1261, in Claverley, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Robert Whitmore, was 21 and his mother, Ada de Walleshall, was 11257. He married Agnes De Haselwell in 1290, in Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons."},"et":{"Bef 1261–":"enne 1261–Surnud","1261–Male":"1261–Surnud","1263–Male":"1263–Surnud","1265–Male":"1265–Surnud","1267–Female":"1267–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1252–Female":"1252–Surnud","1293–Male":"1293–Surnud","1303–Male":"1303–Surnud","1240–Male":"1240–Surnud","1244–F